@Logo_Daedalus The definition for sci-fi that Saint Seraphim Rose gives is all literature that: 1. Religion is absent and if God exists He is impersonal 2. Anthropocentrism, Nietzscheanism (evolved man) 3. Future as projection of the present-day science 4. Utopianism

Through this we can conclude that every literature piece, be it a romance, thriller or whatever you want, if it contains all four, is in the first place a part of the science fiction genre and MAY have a secondary genre that is not as important as its "primary" one.

We can see this easily by observing the attitude sci-fi fans have towards their favourite stories:

they often ignore the characters/plot and instead focus on the "background", analyzing how the portrayed futuristic world works and what it is composed of.

Warhammer 40k is in a different boat, I am not acquainted with it but from what I've seen it is far from the typical sci-fi, which also explains its popularity in more right-wing/traditionalist circles
